Choose the most specific failure_category that fits. For example, set failure_category to `dependency_failure` rather than `build_failure` if the build fails due to a missing package.

Your default assumption is that the failure is NOT caused by recent code changes. Only choose to create a fix if you can
identify a specific, concrete causal mechanism between the code changes and the failure.
If there is an associated merge request, focus your analysis on the MR's changes specifically.

When a pipeline has multiple failing jobs, classify each failure independently. If at least one failure
is fixable, set decision to `create_plan` — the plan will only cover the fixable failures, and the
remaining failures will be addressed separately with comments.

Before making your decision, reason through the following steps for each identified failure:
<reasoning_steps>
  <step>Identify which files were changed and which files/tests are involved in the failure. If there is an associated merge request, focus on the MR's changed files.</step>
  <step>Determine if there is a direct dependency between the code changes and the failure (e.g., the failing test imports or exercises code that was changed).</step>
  <step>Consider alternative explanations: Is this a flaky test? An infrastructure issue? A pre-existing failure on the merge request target branch (master-broken spec)?</step>
  <step>State the strongest argument that the code changes ARE causing this failure, and the strongest argument that they are NOT.</step>
  <step>Only after completing this analysis, make your decision.</step>
</reasoning_steps>

Do NOT attempt to fix any of the following types of failures:
- There is a merge request and the failure is not caused by the code changes (e.g., a broken master/main branch, a pre-existing failure on the target branch)
- The failure appears to be a flaky test or timing-related (e.g., intermittent timeouts, `passed on retry` history)
- The failure is due to infrastructure issues (runner configuration, resources, permissions, network)
- There are changed files and there is no direct dependency between them and the failing test or build step

Set the decision field based on these criteria:
<possible_responses>
  <possible_response>
    <decision>create_plan</decision>
    <response_reason>
      Set decision to `create_plan` when AT LEAST ONE of the failures meets ALL of these criteria:
      - If there are associated changes, you can identify a concrete causal mechanism linking the changes to at least one failure
      - The failure does not appear to be a flaky test, or infrastructure-related
      - If there is a merge request, the changed files directly affect the failing test or build step
      - You are very confident your fix will resolve the issue
    </response_reason>
  </possible_response>
  <possible_response>
    <decision>add_comment</decision>
    <response_reason>
      Set decision to `add_comment` when ANY of the following apply:
      - None of the failures needs to be fixed, as per criteria above
      - When conditions for `create_plan` are not met
    </response_reason>
  </possible_response>
</possible_responses>

<common_false_positive_traps>
  - Do NOT assume files are related just because they are in the same directory or module. Require a concrete import or call-chain dependency.
  - Do NOT attribute infrastructure failures (timeouts, OOM, connection refused, runner errors) to code changes unless the code explicitly changes resource usage.
  - Do NOT attempt to fix flaky tests. If a test appears to fail intermittently regardless of code changes, it is not caused by the code changes.
  - Do NOT attempt to fix failures that exist on the target branch independent of the changes being tested (master-broken specs).
</common_false_positive_traps>

